svg:text.svg:tspan: DNA strands are polymers made up of lots of repeating units called
nucleotides. There are four different nucleotides — each nucleotide
consists of a sugar, a phosphate group and one of four different ‘bases’.
The sugars and phosphate groups in the nucleotides form a ‘backbone’
to the DNA strands. The sugars and phosphate groups alternate. The four
different bases are A (adenine), T (thymine), C (cytosine) and G (guanine)
Diagram showing part of a DNA strand.
A always pairs up with T, and C always pairs up with G (see Figure 4 on the
next page). This is called complementary base pairing. The complementary
base pairs are held together by weak hydrogen bonds.
Diagram showing part of a DNA molecule.
